Hello all, 

I am pleased to announce a new paper called =E2=80=9CDeep Neur=
al Networks are Easily Fooled: High Confidence Predictions for Unrecognizab=
le Images.=E2=80=9D It was written by Anh Nguyen, Jason Yosinski, and mysel=
f. 

The main point of the paper is that Deep Neural Networks see the world=
 very differently than humans, often rating images that are completely unre=
cognizable to us as natural objects (e.g. guitars, penguins) with near-cert=
ainty. 

http://arxiv.org/abs/1412.1897 <http://arxiv.org/abs/1412.1897>

B=
ut probably of even more interest to those on this list is what happens whe=
n you combine Deep Learning with evolution. Check out the amazing diversity=
 of CPPN images you get! I think people on this list will enjoy at least br=
owsing those figures. Note that the evolution is driven by a new type of ev=
olutionary algorithm that Jean-Baptiste Mouret and I have invented called =
=E2=80=9Cmulti-dimensional archive of phenotypic elites=E2=80=9D (MAP-Elite=
s). You can read more about that in this paper: http://arxiv.org/abs/1407.3=
501 <http://arxiv.org/abs/1407.3501>

As we mention in this new paper, we a=
re actively at work combining Deep Neural Networks with Evolution (specific=
ally DNNs + MAP-Elites + CPPNs) to try to automatically create more open-en=
ded evolution. The goal is to algorithmically automate the magic that happe=
ned on PicBreeder and EndlessForms.com <http://endlessforms.com/>. We hope =
to have a paper on that finished in time to submit to GECCO. I will be exci=
ted to share our ideas and data with you once that is ready. 

Congratulati=
ons to new Evolving AI Lab member Anh Nguyen on putting together this paper=
. 

As always, please let us know if you have any questions. 



Best regar=
ds,
Jeff Clune

Assistant Professor, Computer Science
Director, Evolving Ar=
tificial Intelligence Lab <http://evolvingai.org/>
University of Wyoming
je=
ffclune@...
jeffclune.com
